  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Avobenzone, the primary UVA filter in most American sunscreens, degrades significantly when exposed to UV light. The molecule you apply to block the sun breaks down in the sun. This is why most US sunscreens require additional chemical stabilizers just to maintain their rated protection across a beach afternoon. The question is why, in 2025, avobenzone remains the best UVA option Americans can legally buy.</p>
</section>

<section id="uva-uvb-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Protection You're Not Getting</h2>
  <p>There are two ultraviolet wavelength ranges that matter for skin. UVB causes sunburn — the visible, immediate damage that convinced an earlier generation sunscreen was worth the trouble. SPF measures UVB protection exclusively. SPF 50 blocks approximately 98 percent of UVB radiation; SPF 100 blocks about 99 percent. The marginal return diminishes steeply above SPF 50, which is why the debate over high-SPF products mostly generates heat without light.</p>

  <p>UVA rays sneak deeper into your skin like a thief in the night, skipping the sunburn warning and piling up damage you won't see until it's wrinkles or worse. It is the primary driver of photoaging — the wrinkles, the laxity, the textural degradation that cosmetic dermatology spends billions annually trying to reverse. More critically, UVA is a principal contributor to melanoma. Your SPF number tells you nothing about how well your sunscreen addresses this. Nothing at all.</p>

  <p>In Europe, Japan, Australia, and most of Asia, consumers can purchase sunscreens containing bemotrizinol (marketed as Tinosorb S) and bisoctrizole (Tinosorb M) — large, photostable molecules that provide broad-spectrum UVA and UVB coverage without the degradation problem. They don't break down in sunlight. They don't require chemical stabilizers to maintain their rated activity. They are not available in the United States.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Your SPF number tells you nothing about UVA protection. Nothing at all."</p></aside>

<section id="regulatory-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Classification That Froze Everything</h2>
  <p>The FDA classifies sunscreen as an over-the-counter drug. The European Union classifies it as a cosmetic. One sentence explains the entire gap.</p>

  <p>Drug approval in the US requires clinical safety trials. Cosmetic approval in the EU requires a safety assessment. The EU pathway is faster and cheaper; it is also, by design, less demanding pre-market. This is a genuine tension — faster cosmetic approval means less pre-market data, which is a legitimate tradeoff, not a simple win. The EU process, often funded by industry self-assessments rather than independent trials, has produced more protective products without a wave of documented harms, though long-term independent studies are limited. That doesn't resolve the tradeoff. It does make the FDA's inertia harder to defend.</p>

  <p>Under the FDA's framework, sunscreen ingredients not already on the market before 1999 require new drug applications — an expensive, time-consuming process built for pharmaceuticals. The agency uses a standard called GRASE: Generally Recognized As Safe and Effective. Of the sixteen active sunscreen ingredients currently used in US products, only two — zinc oxide and titanium dioxide, the mineral filters — hold full GRASE status. The rest exist in a limbo the agency has not resolved.</p>

  <p>In 2002 and 2003, eight applications for new filters were submitted under the TIME Act — a legislative attempt to create a faster review pathway for sunscreen ingredients. The FDA did not act on them. In 2020, the CARES Act created another pathway, specifically designed to accelerate sunscreen filter review. As of this writing, not a single new filter has been approved under it. The applications were filed. The legislative authority was granted. Congress, apparently, was not aware that the FDA had other plans.</p>

  <p>The manufacturers who submitted those applications—often big players like L'Oréal or Johnson & Johnson with vested interests in the status quo—aren't solely to blame, but their lobbying and market dominance contribute to the regulatory stall. They did what regulators asked. The FDA then did not do what Congress asked.</p>
</section>

<section id="fda-own-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Data the Agency Funded and Then Ignored</h2>
  <p>In 2019, the FDA published a study in JAMA — funded by the agency itself — measuring systemic absorption of common chemical sunscreen filters. The results were specific. Avobenzone was detected in the bloodstream at 4.0 nanograms per milliliter. Oxybenzone reached 209.6 ng/mL. Octocrylene registered at 2.9 ng/mL. Ecamsule at 1.5 ng/mL. A follow-up study in 2020 confirmed and extended these findings.</p>

  <p>The threshold that matters is 0.5 ng/mL — the concentration above which FDA guidance requires manufacturers to conduct carcinogenicity and reproductive toxicity studies. Every chemical filter tested exceeded that threshold. Oxybenzone exceeded it by more than 400 times. This is the regulatory trigger, not a toxicological verdict. Systemic absorption raises real safety questions, especially since follow-up studies on carcinogenicity and reproductive toxicity—required by FDA's own rules—haven't been done. What the studies found was that the safety data required by the FDA's own standards does not exist for the most widely used filters in American sunscreens.</p>

  <p>The agency's response was to ask manufacturers to conduct the follow-up studies. Manufacturers largely have not. The FDA has not compelled them to. Here is the catch-22: the same regulatory structure demanding safety data before approving new filters has spent six years not enforcing the safety data requirements for existing ones. The newer, more protective filters can't get approved because they lack clinical data. The older, demonstrably inferior filters remain on shelves because no one is forcing them to generate clinical data either. The FDA built a door, lost the key, and then blocked the window.</p>

  <p>On oxybenzone specifically: coral reef studies and in vitro research raised endocrine-disruption concerns serious enough that the FDA funded the absorption study. Those concerns have not been established as proven human reproductive harm. Keep that distinction in mind. Americans are not being poisoned by their sunscreen. They are, however, using an inferior product because the agency that was supposed to improve it created a standard it won't enforce and a process it won't complete.</p>

  <p>Mineral sunscreens — zinc oxide and titanium dioxide — avoid the bloodstream absorption issue and hold GRASE status. They are not the obvious off-ramp. High-concentration zinc oxide formulas carry a well-documented cosmetic problem: the white cast that reduces real-world compliance, which matters more than any laboratory protection rating. UVA coverage also varies significantly depending on particle size and concentration. Nanoparticle formulations improve aesthetics but introduce their own open questions. Mineral filters are a reasonable choice; they are not a free pass.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-to-do" class="reveal">
  <h2>What to Actually Do</h2>
  <p>"Broad spectrum" on a US product is an FDA-required designation that guarantees some UVA protection — but the standard is not rigorous, and UVA coverage varies considerably between formulas. It is a floor, not a ceiling.</p>

  <p>The PA rating system — developed in Japan and widely used across Asia — provides more granular UVA information. PA+ through PA++++ indicates increasing protection against Persistent Pigment Darkening, a proxy for UVA dose. PA+++ offers strong UVA coverage; PA++++ is the highest tier. These ratings are appearing with increasing frequency on imported and internationally formulated products available in the US through specialty retailers and online. If you see it, it is meaningful.</p>

  <p>Purchasing European-formulated sunscreens online is legal, increasingly practical, and for UVA protection, genuinely superior. Products containing bemotrizinol or bisoctrizole — look for "Tinosorb S" or "Tinosorb M" on the ingredient list — provide photostable, broad-spectrum coverage that the domestic market cannot match. The main practical considerations are cost, shipping, and SPF labeling conventions that differ slightly from US standards. None of these are prohibitive obstacles.</p>

  <p>The recommendation that hasn't changed: wear sunscreen. The gap documented here is between adequate and optimal, not between safe and dangerous. Unprotected UV exposure causes more documented harm than any of the open questions about chemical filter absorption. The public health math is not close.</p>

  <p>The FDA has had the absorption data since 2019. Filter applications since 2002. Legislative authority to act since 2020. In that time it has approved nothing, compelled nothing, and resolved nothing. The gap between an American drugstore shelf and a European one is not an accident of science. It is a policy outcome — produced by the same agency that demanded the evidence, sat on it, and called that caution.</p>
</section>

